subSubSection.paragraph:
Postabdomen (
Figs 153, 158
, 
161, 165
) relatively short and wide. T6 large, broad (broader in European specimens— 
Fig. 161
), with paler posterior margin. S6 transverse, broader than S5, dark and often with paler posterior margin as in T6. T7 and S7 completely fused into dark brown ring-shaped tergosternum, dorsally in Nearctic and E. Palaearctic often with distinctly paler posterior and sometimes also anterior band (
Fig. 153
), ventrally usually with dark, transverse anteromedial stripe (
Figs 158
, 
165
) which can also be sometimes reduced and with long setae at posterior margin. Anterior margin of original S7 sometimes with a pair of small appendages (cf. 
Fig. 158
). 8th segment partly membranous and densely micropubescent. T8 plate-shaped, dark except for posterior margin, wider and anteriorly less tapered in European (
Fig. 161
) than in Nearctic (
Fig. 153
) specimens. S8 much shorter than T8, medially divided to form 2 finely setose sclerites being recurved and deeply invaginated (see 
Figs 154, 158
, 
162
). Genital chamber (uterus) slender, with internal sclerotization (
Figs 154–156
, 
162–164
) formed by 1 pair of relatively simple, flat but curved sclerites and 1 elongate, narrow and (particularly posteriorly) curved annular sclerite lying below them. Ventral receptacle (
Figs 159
, 
164
) hyaline, slender, long, strongly curved, gradually tapering towards blunt apex (obviously somewhat thicker and shorter in Nearctic specimens); accessory gland hyaline, with some grains on surface, on slender more or less ringed duct. Spermathecae (1+1) shortpyriform, with dark transversely striated surface and slender base provided with rosette of 5–6 characteristic bellshaped appendages (see 
Figs 152, 157
, 
160
) some of which can have doubled apex in Nearctic specimens (
Fig. 152
); cervix short and pale-pigmented; duct of spermatheca broad and short (
Figs 156
, 
164
). T10 small, transverse, dark, with distinctive micropubescence and 1 pair of very long (longer in Nearctic specimens, 
Fig. 154
) medial setae. S10 larger than T10, roughly pentagonal, micropubescent and finely setulose. Cercus relatively short and robust, with fine setae, apical and dorsopreapical being longest (
Figs 154
, 
162
).
